&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Putin complained to the Pope about Ukraine and spoke of peace.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On June 4, Vladimir Putin had his first telephone conversation with the new Pope Leo XIV. As &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.me/news_kremlin/5793&quot;&gt;reported&lt;/a&gt; by the Kremlin, the President of Russia expressed &quot;interest in achieving peace through political and diplomatic means&quot; and accused Ukraine of escalating the conflict.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Putin conveyed greetings from Patriarch Kirill and thanked the Vatican for its willingness to assist in the settlement. He separately noted the exchange of prisoners and the bodies of the dead, achieved at the second round of negotiations in Istanbul.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In addition, Putin complained that &quot;the Kyiv regime is carrying out sabotage against the civilian infrastructure of the Russian Federation&quot; and called on the Pope to intercede for the Ukrainian Orthodox Church.&lt;/p&gt;

